{"id":"1902.07768","submitter":"Thomas Speck","authors":"Thomas Speck","title":"Dynamic facilitation theory: A statistical mechanics approach to dynamic\n  arrest","comments":null,"journal-ref":"J. Stat. Mech. 084015 (2019)","doi":"10.1088/1742-5468/ab2ace","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The modeling of supercooled liquids approaching dynamic arrest has a long\ntradition, which is documented through a plethora of competing theoretical\napproaches. Here, we review the modeling of supercooled liquids in terms of\ndynamic \"defects\", also called excitations or soft spots, that are able to\nsustain motion. To this end, we consider a minimal statistical mechanics\ndescription in terms of active regions with the order parameter related to\ntheir typical size. This is the basis for both Adam-Gibbs and dynamical\nfacilitation theory, which differ in their relaxation mechanism as the liquid\nis cooled: collective motion of more and more particles vs. concerted\nhierarchical motion over larger and larger length scales. For the latter,\ndynamic arrest is possible without a growing static correlation length, and we\nsketch the derivation of a key result: the parabolic law for the structural\nrelaxation time. We critically discuss claims in favor of a growing static\nlength and argue that the resulting scenarios for pinning and dielectric\nrelaxation are in fact compatible with dynamic facilitation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Feb 2019 20:30:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-09-04"}
